# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mercurial-vcs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] In software development, **distributed version control** (also known as **distributed revision control**) is a form of version control in which the complete codebase, including its full history, is mirrored on every developer's computer.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Compared to **centralized version control**, this enables automatic management branching and merging, speeds up most operations (except pushing and fetching), improves the ability to work offline, and does not rely on a single location for backups.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Git, the world's most popular version control system, is a distributed version control system.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Distributed version control systems (DVCS) use a peer-to-peer approach to version control, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Distributed revision control synchronizes repositories by transferring patches from peer to peer.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] There is no single central version of the codebase; instead, each user has a working copy and the full change history.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Some originally centralized systems now offer some distributed features.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Team Foundation Server and Visual Studio Team Services now host centralized and distributed version control repositories via hosting Git.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] A distributed model is generally better suited for large projects with partly independent developers, such as the Linux Kernel.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] It allows developers to work in independent branches and apply changes that can later be committed, audited and merged (or rejected) by others.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] This model allows for better flexibility and permits for the creation and adaptation of custom source code branches (forks) whose purpose might differ from the original project.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] In addition, it permits developers to locally clone an existing code repository and work on such from a local environment where changes are tracked and committed to the local repository allowing for better tracking of changes before being committed to the master branch of the repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Such an approach enables developers to work in local and disconnected branches, making it more convenient for larger distributed teams.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] In a truly distributed project, such as Linux, every contributor maintains their own version of the project, with different contributors hosting their own respective versions and pulling in changes from other users as needed, resulting in a general consensus emerging from multiple different nodes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] This also makes the process of "forking" easy, as all that is required is one contributor stop accepting pull requests from other contributors and letting the codebases gradually grow apart.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] This arrangement, however, can be difficult to maintain, resulting in many projects choosing to shift to a paradigm in which one contributor is the universal "upstream", a repository from whom changes are almost always pulled.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Under this paradigm, development is somewhat recentralized, as every project now has a central repository that is informally considered as the official repository, managed by the project maintainers collectively.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] While distributed version control systems make it easy for new developers to "clone" a copy of any other contributor's repository, in a central model, new developers always clone the central repository to create identical local copies of the code base.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Under this system, code changes in the central repository are periodically synchronized with the local repository, and once the development is done, the change should be integrated into the central repository as soon as possible.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Organizations utilizing this centralize pattern often choose to host the central repository on a third party service like GitHub, which offers not only more reliable uptime than self-hosted repositories, but can also add centralized features like issue trackers and continuous integration.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a **pull request**, also known as a **merge request**.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] The first open-source DVCS systems included Arch, Monotone, and Darcs.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] However, open source DVCSs were never very popular until the release of Git and Mercurial.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] BitKeeper was used in the development of the Linux kernel from 2002 to 2005.
[src:mercurial-vcs/distributed-version-control] The development of Git, now the world's most popular version control system, was prompted by the decision of the company that made BitKeeper to rescind the free license that Linus Torvalds and some other Linux kernel developers had previously taken advantage of.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Git is a very popular DistributedSCM that works very similarly to Mercurial.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Both are built upon such similar concepts that most repositories can be converted to and from Mercurial and Git without any significant data loss!
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] There are, however, significant design and conceptual differences that may cause trouble when coming from Git to Mercurial.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Mercurial and Git differ mainly in nomenclature, interface, and - of course - implementation details, including features.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Mercurial has always focused heavily on interface aspects.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] This makes Mercurial easier to learn - even for someone who has never used version control before.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Git tends to expose lower-level implementation details to users, requiring knowledge of them in order to use Git effectively (e.g. refs).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In comparison to Git, Mercurial requires a shallower understanding to operate in a useful manner.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Mercurial is also safer by default: functionality like history rewriting (which is considered an advanced topic for a version control newcomer) must be enabled.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] To Mercurial newcomers with Git experience, this often gives the false appearance that Mercurial is less powerful or featureful than it really is.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] This section tries to prove that the only logical architecture difference between the two systems, is nomenclature.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] One of the first Git lessons is the repository basic object types: blob, tree and commit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] These are the building blocks for the history model.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Mercurial also builds up history upon the same three concepts, respectively: file, manifest and changeset.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] To identify these objects both systems use a SHA1 hash value, what Mercurial calls nodeid.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Additionally, Mercurial also provides a **local** revision number, a simply incrementing integer, for each changeset, in addition to the reverse count notation provided by Git (like HEAD~4).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] From that, Mercurial's view of history is, just like Git's, a DAG or Directed Acyclic Graph of changesets.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] For instance, the graphical representation of history is the same in the two.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Also like in Git, Mercurial supports branching in different ways.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] First and foremost, each clone of a repository represents a branch, potentially identical to other clones of the same repositories.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] This way of branching is sometimes referred to as *heavy branches* and works almost the same in both systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Then Git has its famous *lightweight branches*, which allow switching between development lines within the same clone of a repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In Git, branches X and Y are simply references to the e and g commits.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In Mercurial, the X and Y branches are called *heads* and they can be referred by their changeset identifier: either local (number) or global (SHA1 hash).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In brief, it is like using Git detached heads instead of branch names, but much easier and without the risk of garbage collection (see hg help heads).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] They can be referred also by a bookmark, which can be pushed and pulled with the -B/--bookmark option.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Finally, Mercurial has another branching functionality called NamedBranches, also known as long lived branches.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] This kind of branch does not have a Git equivalent.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Like with branches both Git and Mercurial support two tag levels: *local* and *global*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Local tags are only visible where they were created and do not propagate, so they behave practically the same in both systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Global tags is one of the aspects that really differs from Git.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Apparently they serve the same purpose, however they are treated differently.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In Git, global tags have a dedicated repository object type; these tags are usually referred as *annotated tags*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In Mercurial, though, they are stored in a special text file called .hgtags residing in the root directory of a repository clone.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Because the .hgtags file is versioned as a normal file, all the file modifications are stored as part of the repository history.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Two important things need to be remembered about how .hgtags is handled: The file only grows and should not be edited, except when it generates a merge conflict.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Because it is revision controlled, there is a corresponding revlog.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] When looking for tags, only the latest revision of .hgtags is parsed; never mind the checked out copy revision.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Although it is questioned by many people new to Mercurial, this design allows to keep track of all global tagging operations.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Nevertheless, it also confuses because it can lead to some puzzling scenarios.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In the graph, T is a global tag pointing to changeset c.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] This tagging action generated changeset d because .hgtags had to be committed.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Therefore, in the new repository tag T does not exist.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] The reason behind this is because in the original repository tag T points to changeset c; however, tag T is added by commit d which is a descendant of c.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] As the clone command limits the history up to changeset c, the addition of the tag is not included in the new repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Things work similarly when tagging a particular revision using hg tag --rev ...
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Regarding tag propagation across repositories, Mercurial has very simple semantics.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] From the history and WireProtocol point of view, the .hgtags file is treated like the rest of the tracked files, which means that any global tagging operation becomes visible to everyone just like any other commit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] It also implies that merge conflicts can occur in .hgtags.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] The rationale behind Mercurial's global tags is briefly justified in this thread (January 2009).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] See also: Giving a persistent name to a revision.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In most design decisions, Mercurial tries to avoid exposing excessive complexity to the user.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] This can sometimes lead to the belief that both systems have nothing in common when in practice the difference is subtle, and vice versa.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] The main difference is that mercurial does not offer an "undo" to what you did without using commands that are referred to as "dangerous", "not what you want" etc in the help pages.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] While the branching model is very similar, moving history between different repositories is slightly mismatched.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Git adds the notion of *tracking branch*, a branch that is used to follow changes from another repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Tracking branches allow to selectively pull or push branches from or to a remote repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Mercurial keeps things simpler in this aspect: When you pull, you bring all remote heads into your local repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Then you can decide whether to merge or not.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Or else, pull and merge automatically using "-u".
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] All pushes that would create new heads (i.e. lightweight branches) stop with a warning, except if the user explicitly forces them.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Git is the only DistributedSCM that exposes the concept of *index* or *staging area*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] The others may implement and hide it, but in no other case is the user aware or has to deal with it.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Mercurial's rough equivalent is the DirState, which controls working copy status information to determine the files to be included in the next commit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] But in any case, this file is handled automatically.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Additionally, it is possible to be more selective at commit time either by specifying the files you want to commit on the command line or by using hg commit --interactive.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] If you felt uncomfortable dealing with Git's index, you are switching for the better.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] If you need the index, you can gain its behavior (with many additional options) with mercurial queues (MQ).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Simple addition of changes to the index can be imitated by just building up a commit with hg commit --amend (optionally with --secret, see phases).
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Although this is a minor issue, Mercurial can obviously handle a *bare* repository; that is, a repository **without** a working copy.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] hg update null As push and pull operations do not update the working copy by default, by not updating the working copy you get the same effect of a bare repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] In fact, it is the recommended option for some particular hgwebdir.cgi setups.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] The table presented below is far from being complete due to the large amount of command and switch combinations that Git offers.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Nevertheless, it tries to cover the most shocking changes when moving from Git to Hg: **Git command** **Hg command** **Notes** git pull hg fetch hg pull -u The fetch command is more similar but requires the FetchExtension to be enabled. git fetch hg pull git push hg push -r .
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Interactive mode has been added to commit in 3.4. git commit --amend hg commit --amend git rebase --interactive hg histedit <base cset> Requires the HisteditExtension.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] Graft is available in 2.0 and higher. git rebase <upstream> hg rebase -d <cset> Requires the RebaseExtension. git format-patch <commits> and git send-mail hg email -r <csets> Requires the PatchbombExtension. git am <mbox> hg mimport -m <mbox> Requires the MboxExtension and the MqExtension.
[src:mercurial-vcs/gitconcepts] While the output of git commands often gives hints as to which commands one could use next, hg does this only in rare cases.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial's major design goals include high performance and scalability, decentralization, fully distributed collaborative development, robust handling of both plain text and binary files, and advanced branching and merging capabilities, while remaining conceptually simple.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] It includes an integrated web-interface.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial has also taken steps to ease the transition for users of other version control systems, particularly Subversion.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial is primarily a command-line driven program, but graphical user interface extensions are available, e.g.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] TortoiseHg, and several IDEs offer support for version control with Mercurial.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] All of Mercurial's operations are invoked as arguments to its driver program `hg` (a reference to Hg – the chemical symbol of the element mercury).
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Olivia Mackall originated Mercurial and served as its lead developer until late 2016.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial is released as free software under the GPL-2.0-or-later license.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] It is mainly implemented using the Python programming language, but includes a binary diff implementation written in C.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mackall first announced Mercurial on 19 April 2005.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] The impetus for this was the announcement earlier that month by Bitmover that they were withdrawing the free version of BitKeeper because of the development of SourcePuller.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] BitKeeper had been used for the version control requirements of the Linux kernel project.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mackall decided to write a distributed version control system as a replacement for use with the Linux kernel.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] This project started a few days after the now well-known Git project was initiated by Linus Torvalds with similar aims.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] The Linux kernel project decided to use Git rather than Mercurial, but Mercurial is now used by many other projects (see below).
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] High-profile projects such as the OpenJDK have used Mercurial in the past, though the OpenJDK no longer does as of Java 16.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial uses SHA-1 hashes to identify revisions.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] For repository access via a network, Mercurial uses an HTTP-based protocol that seeks to reduce round-trip requests, new connections, and data transferred.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial can also work over SSH where the protocol is very similar to the HTTP-based protocol.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] By default it uses a 3-way merge before calling external merge tools.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Figure 1 shows some of the most important operations in Mercurial and their relations to Mercurial's concepts.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Although Mercurial was not selected to manage the Linux kernel sources, it was adopted by several organizations.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Facebook is using the Rust programming language to write Mononoke, a Mercurial server specifically designed to support large multi-project repositories.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] In 2013, Facebook adopted Mercurial and began work on scaling it to handle their large, unified code repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Google also uses Mercurial client as a front-end on their cloud-based 'Piper' monorepo back-end.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Bitbucket announced that its web-based version control services would end support for Mercurial in June 2020 (then extended to July 2020), explaining that "less than 1% of new projects use it, and developer surveys indicated that 90% of developers use Git".
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Xen used Mercurial for many years, but moved to Git in 2013.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mozilla used Mercurial for many years, but started moving to end support for Mercurial in favor of Git in 2023.
[src:mercurial-vcs/mercurial] Mercurial website mentions some other forges.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] This tutorial is an introduction to using Mercurial.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] We don't assume any particular background in using SCM software.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] It is also strongly recommended that you have a look at the Mercurial man pages hg(1) and hgrc(5), which are also available in the release tarballs as doc/hg.1.html and doc/hgrc.5.html.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] You can also use hg help <command> on the command line.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] Command names and parameters are displayed in fixed font.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] A line of input that you should type into your shell or command prompt is displayed in a fixed font, and the line will start with a $ character.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] A line of output that you should expect Mercurial or your shell to display is displayed in a fixed font, but with no special character at the start of the line.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] The concepts remain the same for other Unix shells and the Windows cmd.exe, but the syntax of some operations may change.
[src:mercurial-vcs/tutorial] For example, ls in a Unix shell is roughly equivalent to dir under Windows, and Unix vi is similar to Windows edit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Mercurial's decentralized development model can be confusing to new users.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] This page attempts to illustrate some of the basic concepts.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] See the Tutorial for step-by-step instructions.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] The store contains the **complete** history of the project.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Unlike traditional SCMs, where there's only one central copy of this history, every working directory is paired with a private copy of the history.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] This allows development to go on in parallel.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] The working directory contains a copy of the project's files at a given point in time (eg rev 2), ready for editing.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Because tags and ignored files are revision-controlled, they are also included.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Note here that revision 4 is a **branch** of revision 2, which was the revision in the working directory.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Now revision 4 is the working directory's **parent**.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Mercurial groups related changes to multiple files into single atomic changesets, which are revisions of the whole project.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] These each get a sequential revision number.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Because Mercurial allows distributed parallel development, these revision numbers may disagree between users.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] So Mercurial also assigns each revision a global changeset ID.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Changeset IDs are 40-digit hexadecimal numbers, but they can be abbreviated to any unambiguous prefix, like "e38487".
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Branches and merges in the revision history can occur at any point.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Each unmerged branch creates a new head of the revision history.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Mercurial considers revision 6 to be the tip of the repository, the head with the highest revision number.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Revision 4 is a merge changeset, as it has *two* parent changesets (revisions 2 and 3).
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Bob can now work independently of Alice.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Bob then pulls Alice's repo to synchronize.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] This copies all of Alice's changes into Bob's repository store (here, it's just a single change g).
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Because Alice's **g** is the newest head in Bob's repository, it's now the **tip**.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Bob then does a merge, which combines the last change he was working on (f) with the tip in his repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Note that Alice's working directory was not changed by the pull.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] She has to do an update to synchronize her working directory to the merge changset h.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] This changes the parent changeset of her working directory to changeset h and updates the files in her working directory to revision h.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Now Alice and Bob are fully synchronized again.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Mercurial is a completely decentralized system, and thus has no internal notion of a central repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Unlike a centralized version control system in which experimentation can be disastrous, with a DVCS like Mercurial, you just clone and experiment.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] If you like the results, push them back, otherwise wipe the cloned repository and try something else.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] Many SVN/CVS users expect to host related projects together in one repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] This is really not what Mercurial was made for, so you should try a different way of working.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] In particular, this means that you cannot check out only one directory of a repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] If you absolutely need to host multiple projects in a kind of meta-repository though, you could try the Subrepositories feature that was introduced with Mercurial 1.3 or the older ForestExtension.
[src:mercurial-vcs/understandingmercurial] For a hands-on introduction to using Mercurial, see the Tutorial.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:mercurial-vcs/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
